import{a as e}from"./chunk-CG3CMPJA.js";import"./chunk-IFGU66OU.js";var t={meta:e,sections:[{id:"overview",title:"Overview",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"**Delivery semantics** describe how many times a messaging system may deliver a message under failure: **at-most-once** (0 or 1), **at-least-once** (1 or more), and **exactly-once** / **effectively-once** (business effect applied once). Brokers advertise guarantees for **produce \u2192 log \u2192 consume**, but **end-to-end** exactly-once across your DB, side effects, and retries is harder \u2014 you usually combine **idempotent consumers**, **dedupe keys**, and careful offset commits."},{type:"callout",variant:"info",title:"Effectively-once",body:"True mathematical exactly-once across every hop is rare. What production systems deliver is **effectively-once**: duplicates may be *attempted*, but **side effects** (ledger row, email send flag, inventory decrement) happen **once** because of idempotency or transactional outbox patterns."},{type:"table",caption:"The three semantics.",headers:["Semantic","Deliveries","Typical failure mode","When to use"],rows:[["At-most-once","0 or 1","Lost messages on crash","Metrics, logs, best-effort signals"],["At-least-once","\u2265 1","Duplicates after retry","Default for queues + idempotent handlers"],["Exactly / effectively-once","1 effect","Complex; needs dedupe/txn","Payments, inventory, unique emails"]]}]},{id:"concept",title:"Concept and why exactly-once is hard",blocks:[{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"Real-world analogy",body:"Mailing a check: **at-most-once** = send once, never resend if unsure (check may be lost). **At-least-once** = keep resending until the bank confirms (risk of two deposits). **Effectively-once** = resend freely but the bank uses a **check number** so a second deposit is rejected."},{type:"mermaid",caption:"At-least-once retry creates duplicates without idempotency.",definition:`sequenceDiagram
  participant P as Producer
  participant B as Broker
  participant C as Consumer
  participant DB as Database
  P->>B: publish order-42
  B->>C: deliver
  C->>DB: insert payment
  Note over C: crash before ack
  B->>C: redeliver order-42
  C->>DB: insert payment again
  Note over DB: duplicate unless idempotent`},{type:"markdown",value:`**Why end-to-end exactly-once is hard:**

1. **Producer retries** after a timeout whose ack was lost \u2192 broker may already have the message.
2. **Consumer processes**, then crashes **before offset commit** \u2192 redelivery.
3. **Side effects** (HTTP call, email) are not rolled back when the consumer retries.
4. **Multi-system transactions** (broker + DB + third party) lack a shared atomic commit without heavy protocols.

**Mitigations:** idempotency keys, unique constraints, dedupe stores (Redis/Bloom + TTL), transactional outbox, Kafka **idempotent + transactional producers**, and **process \u2192 commit offset** ordering (or transactionally tied offsets).`}]},{id:"kafka",title:"Kafka: acks, offsets, transactions",blocks:[{type:"table",caption:"Kafka knobs that shape delivery.",headers:["Knob","Setting","Effect"],rows:[["acks","0","Fire-and-forget; at-most-once produce"],["acks","1","Leader ack only; risk of loss on leader fail"],["acks","all / -1","ISR replicas ack; stronger durability"],["enable.idempotence","true","Broker dedupes producer retries (PID + seq)"],["transactional.id","set","Atomic multi-partition writes + EOS consume-transform-produce"],["Consumer offset","auto vs manual","Commit after success \u2192 at-least-once; before \u2192 at-most-once"]]},{type:"callout",variant:"warning",title:"Kafka \u201Cexactly-once\u201D scope",body:"Kafka EOS (**idempotent producer + transactions**) covers **read\u2013process\u2013write within Kafka** (and offset commits in the same transaction). Writing to an **external Postgres** still needs an **idempotent upsert** or **outbox** \u2014 the broker cannot make your DB call exactly-once by itself."},{type:"markdown",value:"**Practical pattern:** produce with `acks=all` + idempotence; consumers use **manual commits** after a successful **idempotent** DB write keyed by `message.key` or business `eventId`. For pipelines that stay inside Kafka, use **transactional** consume-transform-produce."}]},{id:"when-to-use",title:"Choosing a semantic",blocks:[{type:"table",caption:"When to use each.",headers:["Workload","Preferred semantic","Why"],rows:[["Clickstream / metrics","At-most-once or at-least-once","Loss or dupes are tolerable; prioritize throughput"],["Job queues / emails","At-least-once + idempotency","Must not lose; dupes filtered by send-id"],["Payments / inventory","Effectively-once","Unique constraint or ledger idempotency key"],["Log aggregation","At-least-once","Downstream aggregation often dedupes"],["CDC / stream ETL","At-least-once or Kafka EOS","Replay-safe sinks with upsert keys"]]},{type:"prosCons",title:"Trade-offs",pros:["At-least-once is simple and durable \u2014 default for most queues.","Idempotency keys make duplicates cheap to ignore.","Kafka transactions simplify internal stream processing."],cons:["Exactly-once marketing often hides scope limits.","Dedupe stores add storage and TTL operational cost.","Strict EOS increases latency and operational complexity."]}]},{id:"interview-questions",title:"Interview Questions",blocks:[{type:"interviewQa",items:[{question:"Define at-most-once vs at-least-once.",answer:"**At-most-once:** message may be lost; never duplicated (ack before process, or no retry). **At-least-once:** retries until success; duplicates possible. Most reliable systems choose at-least-once and make handlers **idempotent**."},{question:"Is Kafka exactly-once end-to-end?",answer:"Kafka EOS is **within the Kafka ecosystem** (produce/consume/offset in a transaction). External side effects still need **idempotency**. Say \u201Ceffectively-once\u201D for business outcomes."},{question:"How do idempotency keys work?",answer:"Client sends a unique key (UUID) with the request. Server stores **key \u2192 result** (or unique DB constraint). Retries with the same key return the original result instead of applying the effect twice."},{question:"Where should the consumer commit the offset?",answer:"**After** successful processing for at-least-once. Committing **before** processing yields at-most-once (crash loses the message). Ideal: commit in the **same transaction** as the side effect when possible."},{question:"What does acks=all give you?",answer:"The leader waits for **in-sync replicas** before acknowledging. Reduces data loss on broker failure vs `acks=1`. Pair with `min.insync.replicas` \u2265 2 for production durability."},{question:"How would you design payment event processing?",answer:"At-least-once queue + **paymentId** unique constraint / idempotency table. Process in a DB transaction; commit offset after commit. Optional outbox for outbound events. Never rely on \u201Cexactly-once broker\u201D alone."},{question:"SQS standard vs FIFO delivery?",answer:"Standard: **at-least-once**, best-effort ordering. FIFO: **exactly-once processing** within a 5-minute dedupe window *per message group* \u2014 still design for idempotency outside that window."}]}]},{id:"summary",title:"Summary",blocks:[{type:"callout",variant:"summary",title:"Key takeaways",body:`1. Prefer **at-least-once + idempotency** as the default.
2. **Exactly-once** usually means **effectively-once** for side effects.
3. Kafka: **acks=all**, idempotent producers, careful **offset** timing, transactions for internal EOS.
4. Dedupe with **idempotency keys** and unique constraints.
5. Match semantic to **loss vs duplicate** tolerance of the domain.`}]}]},a=t;export{a as default};
